If you‚Äôre trying to better understand UI/UX Design, there‚Äôs no better place to start than reading The Design of Everyday Things by Don Norman. There‚Äôs a lot to this book, but the biggest things I took away from it was the importance of Affordances and Feedback. At the end of the day, most of your job as a designer is to create interaction points, rank them by importance to the user persona, and then get the ideal user persona to click on those buttons. So the best way to get users to click on buttons in your UX Design is add affordances. Affordances are signifiers that guide users on what interaction points will do. It‚Äôs easy to forget how important this is because designers are often biased towards the context that users will have. When you‚Äôve been working on the same product for months, things that are natural to you are complete unknowns to the users. While some users will be okay clicking around until they figure it out, it‚Äôs best to streamline the user flow by showing tooltips, subheadings, and learn more buttons. This will make it so power users can ignore them while newcomers will gain confidence. Now, once a user taps the buttons or fills out a form, they need to know that it worked. You want to show brand logos on your landing page. This is the easiest and most attractive way to do that. First, stop going to Google images and searching by brand. Instead, use an app called BrandFetch. Pull directly from their website or use their Figma plugin. Next, open the PNG or SVG versions of your logos in Photoshop. Open up Layer Styles, and set a Color Overlay to white or black. This most certainly goes against the brand usage guidelines of many brands, but I‚Äôm not a lawyer, just a janky ass designer. Choose a maximum width to be used for your logos. I like to choose a max width AND height for the container of the logo, and then resize the logo within. One thing I‚Äôll add is when choosing these dimensions, I multiply them by 2 or 3.  So if my max-width of the logo on the web page needs to be 200pixels, I‚Äôll save the image with a max-width of 4 or 600 pixels. This allows me to a crispier resolution of the image on retina displays without sacrificing too much page load performance. And as a side note, you don‚Äôt have to name your image files with 2x or 3x anymore, you simply have to make sure the HTML img tag uses a srcset parameter with the correct value, like 2x or 3x. In UI design, it‚Äôs often little details that make all the difference. A good shadow can make or break a design. The biggest thing that I focus on when adding shadows to my designs is that you need to make users feel the shadow, but not think about the shadow. The best way to do that is make them really soft. Design is not art--design is action. That's why UX design is all about harnessing user desires and moving users down the user flow. The way you direct users is through making better interaction points. Buttons should have some padding to give them attention. That padding should be wider than it is tall so that users who are scanning can easily find the interaction points. You can also make your ui design easier to scan by giving the buttons distinct colors that stand out. You can train users to look for a specific color on the page to increase the speed to finding the interaction points. Just, don't over-use primary color buttons. Replying to @soul_william Here‚Äôs how I approach my font sizes when working with Typography in my ui/ux designs. You have to use font sizes to your advantage to guide the user‚Äôs eye towards key areas. You do this by using information architecture! Information Architecture is much more than just font sizing, but typography plays a huge part in IA design. Information Architecture has us letting the user scan to confirm they‚Äôre on the right page, then scan to find the right section of content they‚Äôre looking for, then scan to find the right piece of content inside that section. This zoom-tier is how I approach all of my designs from the type I use to the colors and shadow I add. With this, we want to make page headers the largest, then section headers a little smaller, then group headers smaller than that. Some people use the fibonacci sequence or the golden ratio to map their header sizes accordingly. I‚Äôm not that particular, though it ends up similar at about 1.5x the size of the next tier. I usually start from section headers as those are the most common for scanning. Once I have that set, I work in increments of 2 or 4 points at a time until I end up with roughly 34+ points or higher in page headers, 16-26 points on sections, and 14-18pt on group headers. From there, I generally keep paragraphs around the same size as group headers or 2 to 4 points smaller and then use a thinner/lighter font weight to keep things easy to read. #informationarchitecture #iadesign #fontsize #typography #uxdesign #uiux  created by Nolan Perkins ‚ñí RadNolan with Nolan Perkins ‚ñí RadNolan‚Äôs original sound
